Preheat the #oven{} to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of water with a large
pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1%cup}(diced). 
Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(minced).

Add the @fusilloni pasta{6%ounce} to the boiling water and cook for ~{9-10%minutes}, 
until al dente. Drain and set aside.

== Onion-Garlic Mixture ==

Meanwhile, heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large oven-proof pan{} over medium heat. 
Add the diced onion and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}, until soft. Add the garlic to the pan 
and cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Set half of the mixture aside.

Add the @ground beef{10%ounce} to the pan with the @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} 
and cook, breaking the meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through. Season 
with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add the @spinach{8%ounce} and a large pinch of 
@nutmeg{1%teaspoon} to the pan and cook, tossing, for ~{2-3%minutes}, until wilted. 
Season with salt and pepper.

Transfer the spinach-beef mixture to a medium #bowl{} and combine with the 
@ricotta cheese{8%ounce}. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Return the reserved onion-garlic mixture to the same pan over medium heat and add 
the @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce}. Simmer for ~{5-7%minutes} then season with salt 
and pepper.

Add the fusilloni to the pan and toss to combine. Dollop with spoonfuls of the 
spinach-beef mixture, then sprinkle with the @mozzarella cheese{2%ounce}. 

> If you do not have an ovenproof pan, complete this step in a small baking dish.

Transfer the pan to the oven for about ~{5%minutes}, until melted and bubbly. Serve 
divided between bowls and enjoy!